{"title_page": "Shaun Spiers", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{BLP sources|date=July 2010}}\n{{Infobox MEP\n| honorific-prefix    =\n| name                = Shaun Spiers\n| honorific-suffix    = \n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| image =\n| constituency_MP     = [[London South East (European Parliament constituency)|London South East]]\n| parliament          = European\n| term_start          = 9 June 1994\n| term_end            = 10 June 1999\n| majority            =\n| predecessor         = [[Peter Price (politician)|Peter Price]]\n| successor           = Constituency Dissolved\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1962|4|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place         =\n| death_date          =\n| death_place         =\n| nationality         = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse              =\n| relations           =\n| children            =\n| residence           =\n| alma_mater          = [[St John's College, Oxford]]<br>[[King's College London]]\n| occupation          =\n| profession          =\n| religion            =\n| signature           =\n| website             =\n| footnotes           =\n}}\n'''Shaun Mark Spiers''' (born 23 April 1962) is the Executive Director of the environmental think-tank, Green Alliance and a former [[Member of the European Parliament]].\n\n==Biography==\nHe was educated at [[Brentwood School (England)|Brentwood School]], read [[Philosophy, Politics and Economics|PPE]] at [[St John's College, Oxford]] and later took a master's degree in War Studies from [[King's College London]] writing ''[[Tom Wintringham]] and the Socialist Way of War'' for the Institute of Historical Research in 1988, a paper which led to Wintringham's papers coming to King's, and formed the basis for much of Wintringham's biography as eventually written by [[Hugh Purcell]]. A keen [[cooperative|cooperator]], he served as Political Officer of the South East Co-op (Co-operative Wholesale Society) from 1987\u20131994. In 1994 he was elected [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]] for [[London South East (European Parliament constituency)|London South East]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/members/archive/alphaOrder/view.do?language=EN&id=2104|title=Your MEPs : Shaun Mark SPIERS|work=[[Europa (web portal)|Europa]]|accessdate=6 July 2010}}</ref> He served on the Agriculture and Rural Development committee. He was not re-elected in 1999 under the list system, and became Chief Executive of the Association of British Credit Unions Limited (ABCUL) which represents the vast majority of credit unions in Great Britain. Spiers was Chief Executive of [[Campaign to Protect Rural England (CPRE)|CPRE]] 2004 to 2017. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cpre.org.uk/news/view/124|title=New chief for countryside campaigners|publisher=Campaign to Protect Rural England|accessdate=6 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120225160501/http://www.cpre.org.uk/news/view/124|archivedate=25 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHis book, How to build houses and save the countryside, was published by Policy Press in March 2018.\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Co-operatives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spiers, Shaun}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Brentwood School, Essex]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St John's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Members of the European Parliament for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MEPs]]\n[[Category:Co-operative Party politicians]]\n[[Category:British charity and campaign group workers]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 1994\u20131999]]\n\n\n{{UK-MEP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{BLP sources|date=July 2010}}\n{{Infobox MEP\n| honorific-prefix    =\n| name                = Shaun Spiers\n| honorific-suffix    = \n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| image =\n| constituency_MP     = [[London South East (European Parliament constituency)|London South East]]\n| parliament          = European\n| term_start          = 9 June 1994\n| term_end            = 10 June 1999\n| majority            =\n| predecessor         = [[Peter Price (politician)|Peter Price]]\n| successor           = Constituency Dissolved\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1962|4|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place         =\n| death_date          =\n| death_place         =\n| nationality         = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse              =\n| relations           =\n| children            =\n| residence           =\n| alma_mater          = [[St John's College, Oxford]]<br>[[King's College London]]\n| occupation          =\n| profession          =\n| religion            =\n| signature           =\n| website             =\n| footnotes           =\n}}\n'''Shaun Mark Spiers''' (born 23 April 1962) is the Executive Director of the environmental think-tank, Green Alliance and a former [[Member of the European Parliament]].\n\n==Biography==\nHe was educated at [[Brentwood School (England)|Brentwood School]], read [[Philosophy, Politics and Economics|PPE]] at [[St John's College, Oxford]] and later took a Master's degree in War Studies from [[King's College London]] writing ''[[Tom Wintringham]] and the Socialist Way of War'' for the Institute of Historical Research in 1988, a paper which led to Wintringham's papers coming to King's, and formed the basis for much of Wintringham's biography as eventually written by [[Hugh Purcell]]. A keen [[cooperative|cooperator]], he served as Political Officer of the South East Co-op (Co-operative Wholesale Society) from 1987-1994. In 1994 he was elected [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]] for [[London South East (European Parliament constituency)|London South East]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/members/archive/alphaOrder/view.do?language=EN&id=2104|title=Your MEPs : Shaun Mark SPIERS|work=[[Europa (web portal)|Europa]]|accessdate=6 July 2010}}</ref> He served on the Agriculture and Rural Development committee. He was not re-elected in 1999 under the list system, and became Chief Executive of the Association of British Credit Unions Limited (ABCUL) which represents the vast majority of credit unions in Great Britain. Spiers was Chief Executive of [[Campaign to Protect Rural England (CPRE)|CPRE]] 2004 to 2017. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cpre.org.uk/news/view/124|title=New chief for countryside campaigners|publisher=Campaign to Protect Rural England|accessdate=6 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120225160501/http://www.cpre.org.uk/news/view/124|archivedate=25 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHis book, How to build houses and save the countryside, was published by Policy Press in March 2018.\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Co-operatives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spiers, Shaun}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Brentwood School, Essex]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St John's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Members of the European Parliament for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MEPs]]\n[[Category:Co-operative Party politicians]]\n[[Category:British charity and campaign group workers]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 1994\u20131999]]\n\n\n{{UK-MEP-stub}}\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:clean up,typo(s) fixed: Master's degree \u2192 master's degree, 1987-1994 \u2192 1987\u20131994", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shaun_Spiers"}
{"title_page": "Captive bolt pistol", "text_new": "{{short description|Device used for stunning animals before slaughter}}\n{{Refimprove|date=November 2009}}\n[[Image:Schlachtschussapparat (modified).jpg|upright=0.4|thumb|Captive bolt pistol]]\n[[Image:TED Stunner Captive Bolt Technology.jpg#file|thumb|right|240px|Modern captive bolt device]]\n\nA '''captive bolt pistol''' or '''gun''' (also variously known as a '''cattle gun''', '''stunbolt gun''', '''bolt gun''', or '''stunner''') is a device used for [[stunning]] animals prior to [[Slaughter (livestock)|slaughter]].\n\nThe goal of captive bolt stunning is to inflict a forceful strike on the [[forehead]] with the bolt in order to induce [[unconsciousness]]. The bolt may or may not destroy part of the [[brain]].\n\nThe bolt consists of a heavy rod made of corrosion-resistant alloys, such as [[stainless steel]]. It is held in position inside the barrel of the stunner by means of rubber [[washer (hardware)|washer]]s. The bolt is usually not visible in a stunner in good condition. The bolt is actuated by a [[trigger (firearms)|trigger]] pull and is propelled forward by compressed air, a spring mechanism, or by the discharge of a [[blank (cartridge)|blank round]] ignited by a [[firing pin]]. After striking a shallow but forceful blow on the forehead of the animal, spring tension causes the bolt to recoil back into the barrel.\n\nThe captive bolt pistol was invented in 1903 by Dr. Hugo Heiss, former director of a [[slaughterhouse]] in [[Straubing]], Germany.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ryder|first1=Richard D.|title=Animal revolution : changing attitudes toward speciesism|date=2000|publisher=New York|location=Oxford|isbn=9781859733301}}{{Page needed|date=December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Variations==\nCaptive bolt pistols are of three types: penetrating, non-penetrating, and free bolt. The use of penetrating captive bolts has largely been discontinued in commercial situations in order to minimize the risk of transmission of disease.\n\nIn the '''penetrating''' type, the stunner uses a pointed bolt which is propelled by pressurized air, spring mechanism, or a blank cartridge. The bolt penetrates the [[skull]] of the animal, enters the cranium, and catastrophically damages the [[Telencephalon|cerebrum]] and part of the [[cerebellum]]. [[Concussion]] causes destruction of vital centers of the [[brain]] and an increase in [[intracranial pressure]], causing the animal to lose consciousness. This method is currently the most effective type of stunning, since it physically destroys [[white matter|brain matter]] (increasing the probability of a successful stun), while also leaving the [[brain stem]] intact and thus ensuring the heart continues to pump during the [[Exsanguination#The slaughtering of animals in the meat industry|exsanguination]].<ref name=\"Sch\u00fctt-Abraham 1992\">{{Cite journal|last=Sch\u00fctt-Abraham|first=I|last2=Knauer-Kraetzl|first2=B|last3=Wormuth|first3=HJ|date=January 1992|title=[Observations during captive bolt stunning of rabbits]|pmid=1543476|journal=Berliner und Munchener tierarztliche Wochenschrift|language=de|volume=105|issue=1|issn=0005-9366}}</ref> One disadvantage of this method is that brain matter is allowed to enter the [[blood stream]], possibly contaminating other tissue with [[bovine spongiform encephalopathy]] (BSE, colloquially known as mad cow disease).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Anil|first=M. H.|last2=Helps|first2=C. R.|last3=McKinstry|first3=J. L.|last4=Brown|first4=S. N.|last5=Philips|first5=A.|last6=Harbour|first6=D.|last7=Love|first7=S.|last8=Williams|first8=S.|last9=Shand|first9=A.|date=May 2001|title=Jugular venous emboli of brain tissue induced in sheep by the use of captive bolt guns|pmid=11394796|journal=Veterinary Record|volume=148|issue=20|pages=619\u2013620|doi=10.1136/vr.148.20.619|issn=0042-4900}}</ref>\n[[Image:Cash's captive bolt pistol.jpg|thumb|right|A captive bolt pistol]]\n\nThe action of a '''non-penetrating''' stunner is similar, but the bolt is blunt with a mushroom-shaped tip. The bolt strikes the forehead with great force and immediately retracts. The subsequent concussion is responsible for the unconsciousness of the animal. This type of stunner is less reliable at causing immediate unconsciousness than penetrating types; however, it has undergone a resurgence of popularity because of concerns about [[mad cow disease]]. In the [[European Union]], this captive bolt design is required for slaughter of animals that will be used for [[pharmaceutical]] manufacture.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emea.europa.eu/pdfs/human/bwp/TSE%20NFG%20410-rev2.pdf |title=Note for guidance on minimising the risk of transmitting animal spongiform encephalopathy agents via human and veterinary medicinal products |format=PDF |accessdate=2010-09-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091114180833/http://www.emea.europa.eu/pdfs/human/bwp/TSE%20NFG%20410-rev2.pdf# |archive-date=2009-11-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe '''free bolt stunner''' is used for emergency, in-the-field [[animal euthanasia|euthanasia]] of large farm-animals that cannot be restrained. It differs from a true captive bolt gun in that the projectile is not retractable; it is similar in operation to a [[powder-actuated tool|powder-actuated]] [[nail gun]] or conventional firearm. Capable of firing only when pressed firmly against a surface (typically the animal's forehead), the device fires a small projectile through the animal's skull. The [[veterinarian]] can then either leave the animal to die from the projectile wound or administer lethal drugs.\n\n==Use==\nWith cattle, goats, sheep, rabbits, and horses,<ref>{{cite web|last=Beam |first=Christopher |url=http://www.slate.com/id/2212233/ |title=They Shoot Horses, Don't They? |publisher=Slate.com |date=2009-02-25 |accessdate=2010-09-13}}</ref> failure to adequately stun using a penetrating stunner can largely be attributed to incorrect positioning.<ref name=\"Sch\u00fctt-Abraham 1992\"/> Captive bolts allow for meat trimmings from the head to be salvaged. In some [[veal]] operations, a non-penetrating concussive stunner is used in order to preserve the brains for further processing.\n\nCaptive bolt stunners are safer to use in most red meat slaughter situations. There is no danger of [[ricochet]] or over-penetration as there is with regular firearms.\n\nThe cartridges typically use 2 to 3 [[Grain (measure)|grain]]s (130 to 190&nbsp;mg) of [[smokeless powder]] but can use up to 7 grains (450&nbsp;mg) in the case of large animals such as bulls. The velocity of the bolt is usually {{convert|55|m/s|ft/s}} in the case of small animals and {{convert|75|m/s|ft/s}} in the case of large animals.\n\n==Use for homicide==\nThere have been a number of cases where a captive bolt pistol has been used for homicide, including:\n* A 46-year-old German man with a history of alcohol abuse and aggressive behaviour killed his wife.<ref>{{cite web|last=Betz |first=Peter |url=http://epub.ub.uni-muenchen.de/7477/1/eisenmenger_wolfgang_7477.pdf |title=Homicide with  a Captive Bolt Pistol|publisher=Raven Press |date=1993 |accessdate=2012-10-27|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n* An English slaughterman killed a woman with two shots to the chest.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bolt-gun murder 'not predictable'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-suffolk-15636199|accessdate=2017-12-22|work=BBC News|date=8 November 2011}}</ref>\n* On 8 January, 2009, [[Sri Lanka]]n investigative journalist and founder Editor-in-Chief of ''[[The Sunday Leader]]'' [[Lasantha Wickrematunge]] was reportedly assassinated by Sri Lankan military operatives with the use of a captive bolt pistol. {{fact|date=July 2019}}\n\n===In fiction===\n* In the TV series ''[[Bones_(TV_series)|Bones]]'', the mother of protagonist [[Temperance \"Bones\" Brennan]] is discovered to have been murdered with a captive bolt pistol, which convicts a suspected hitman who evaded arrest for decades due to his favored murder weapon being unknown prior to this discovery.\n* In the novel Flesh House by Stuart MacBride, a serial killer uses a bolt gun as a murder weapon on multiple victims. \n* In the novel ''[[No Country for Old Men]]'' and its [[No Country for Old Men (film)|film adaption]], [[Psychopathy|psychopathic]] [[hitman]] [[Anton Chigurh]] uses a captive bolt pistol as a murder weapon, as well as an impromptu breaking-and-entering device.\n* In Austrian director [[Michael Haneke]]'s 1992 film ''[[Benny's Video]]'', the murder of a young girl is perpetrated with a captive bolt pistol.\n* In the 2017 film ''[[It (2017 film)| It]]'', protagonist [[Bill Denbrough (character)|Bill Denbrough]] used the bolt pistol on [[It (character)| Pennywise]].\n* The song \"Captive Bolt Pistol\" by British [[death metal]] band [[Carcass (band)|Carcass]] describes the use of captive bolt pistols for slaughtering cattle and humans.\n* A veterinarian's \"horse gun\" is used as a murder weapon in the episode entitled \"Confection\" of the British TV series ''[[Endeavour (TV series)|Endeavour]]''.\n* In the 2020 film Bloodshot, Martin Axe uses a captive bolt gun to kill Ray\u2019s wife, Gina.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Captive bolt guns}}\n*[https://www.avma.org/KB/Policies/Documents/euthanasia.pdf AVMA Guidelines for the Euthanasia of Animals: 2013 Edition]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Captive Bolt Pistol}}\n[[Category:Firearms]]\n[[Category:Meat industry]]\n[[Category:Animal killing]]\n[[Category:Farming tools]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Device used for stunning animals before slaughter}}\n{{Refimprove|date=November 2009}}\n[[Image:Schlachtschussapparat (modified).jpg|upright=0.4|thumb|Captive bolt pistol]]\n[[Image:TED Stunner Captive Bolt Technology.jpg#file|thumb|right|240px|Modern captive bolt device]]\n\nA '''captive bolt pistol''' or '''gun''' (also variously known as a '''cattle gun''', '''stunbolt gun''', '''bolt gun''', or '''stunner''') is a device used for [[stunning]] animals prior to [[Slaughter (livestock)|slaughter]].\n\nThe goal of captive bolt stunning is to inflict a forceful strike on the [[forehead]] with the bolt in order to induce [[unconsciousness]]. The bolt may or may not destroy part of the [[brain]].\n\nThe bolt consists of a heavy rod made of corrosion-resistant alloys, such as [[stainless steel]]. It is held in position inside the barrel of the stunner by means of rubber [[washer (hardware)|washer]]s. The bolt is usually not visible in a stunner in good condition. The bolt is actuated by a [[trigger (firearms)|trigger]] pull and is propelled forward by compressed air, a spring mechanism, or by the discharge of a [[blank (cartridge)|blank round]] ignited by a [[firing pin]]. After striking a shallow but forceful blow on the forehead of the animal, spring tension causes the bolt to recoil back into the barrel.\n\nThe captive bolt pistol was invented in 1903 by Dr. Hugo Heiss, former director of a [[slaughterhouse]] in [[Straubing]], Germany.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ryder|first1=Richard D.|title=Animal revolution : changing attitudes toward speciesism|date=2000|publisher=New York|location=Oxford|isbn=9781859733301}}{{Page needed|date=December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Variations==\nCaptive bolt pistols are of three types: penetrating, non-penetrating, and free bolt. The use of penetrating captive bolts has largely been discontinued in commercial situations in order to minimize the risk of transmission of disease.\n\nIn the '''penetrating''' type, the stunner uses a pointed bolt which is propelled by pressurized air, spring mechanism, or a blank cartridge. The bolt penetrates the [[skull]] of the animal, enters the cranium, and catastrophically damages the [[Telencephalon|cerebrum]] and part of the [[cerebellum]]. [[Concussion]] causes destruction of vital centers of the [[brain]] and an increase in [[intracranial pressure]], causing the animal to lose consciousness. This method is currently the most effective type of stunning, since it physically destroys [[white matter|brain matter]] (increasing the probability of a successful stun), while also leaving the [[brain stem]] intact and thus ensuring the heart continues to pump during the [[Exsanguination#The slaughtering of animals in the meat industry|exsanguination]].<ref name=\"Sch\u00fctt-Abraham 1992\">{{Cite journal|last=Sch\u00fctt-Abraham|first=I|last2=Knauer-Kraetzl|first2=B|last3=Wormuth|first3=HJ|date=January 1992|title=[Observations during captive bolt stunning of rabbits]|pmid=1543476|journal=Berliner und Munchener tierarztliche Wochenschrift|language=de|volume=105|issue=1|issn=0005-9366}}</ref> One disadvantage of this method is that brain matter is allowed to enter the [[blood stream]], possibly contaminating other tissue with [[bovine spongiform encephalopathy]] (BSE, colloquially known as mad cow disease).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Anil|first=M. H.|last2=Helps|first2=C. R.|last3=McKinstry|first3=J. L.|last4=Brown|first4=S. N.|last5=Philips|first5=A.|last6=Harbour|first6=D.|last7=Love|first7=S.|last8=Williams|first8=S.|last9=Shand|first9=A.|date=May 2001|title=Jugular venous emboli of brain tissue induced in sheep by the use of captive bolt guns|pmid=11394796|journal=Veterinary Record|volume=148|issue=20|pages=619\u2013620|doi=10.1136/vr.148.20.619|issn=0042-4900}}</ref>\n[[Image:Cash's captive bolt pistol.jpg|thumb|right|A captive bolt pistol]]\n\nThe action of a '''non-penetrating''' stunner is similar, but the bolt is blunt with a mushroom-shaped tip. The bolt strikes the forehead with great force and immediately retracts. The subsequent concussion is responsible for the unconsciousness of the animal. This type of stunner is less reliable at causing immediate unconsciousness than penetrating types; however, it has undergone a resurgence of popularity because of concerns about [[mad cow disease]]. In the [[European Union]], this captive bolt design is required for slaughter of animals that will be used for [[pharmaceutical]] manufacture.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emea.europa.eu/pdfs/human/bwp/TSE%20NFG%20410-rev2.pdf |title=Note for guidance on minimising the risk of transmitting animal spongiform encephalopathy agents via human and veterinary medicinal products |format=PDF |accessdate=2010-09-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091114180833/http://www.emea.europa.eu/pdfs/human/bwp/TSE%20NFG%20410-rev2.pdf# |archive-date=2009-11-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe '''free bolt stunner''' is used for emergency, in-the-field [[animal euthanasia|euthanasia]] of large farm-animals that cannot be restrained. It differs from a true captive bolt gun in that the projectile is not retractable; it is similar in operation to a [[powder-actuated tool|powder-actuated]] [[nail gun]] or conventional firearm. Capable of firing only when pressed firmly against a surface (typically the animal's forehead), the device fires a small projectile through the animal's skull. The [[veterinarian]] can then either leave the animal to die from the projectile wound or administer lethal drugs.\n\n==Use==\nWith cattle, goats, sheep, rabbits, and horses,<ref>{{cite web|last=Beam |first=Christopher |url=http://www.slate.com/id/2212233/ |title=They Shoot Horses, Don't They? |publisher=Slate.com |date=2009-02-25 |accessdate=2010-09-13}}</ref> failure to adequately stun using a penetrating stunner can largely be attributed to incorrect positioning.<ref name=\"Sch\u00fctt-Abraham 1992\"/> Captive bolts allow for meat trimmings from the head to be salvaged. In some [[veal]] operations, a non-penetrating concussive stunner is used in order to preserve the brains for further processing.\n\nCaptive bolt stunners are safer to use in most red meat slaughter situations. There is no danger of [[ricochet]] or over-penetration as there is with regular firearms.\n\nThe cartridges typically use 2 to 3 [[Grain (measure)|grain]]s (130 to 190&nbsp;mg) of [[smokeless powder]] but can use up to 7 grains (450&nbsp;mg) in the case of large animals such as bulls. The velocity of the bolt is usually {{convert|55|m/s|ft/s}} in the case of small animals and {{convert|75|m/s|ft/s}} in the case of large animals.\n\n==Use for homicide==\nThere have been a number of cases where a captive bolt pistol has been used for homicide, including:\n* A 46-year-old German man with a history of alcohol abuse and aggressive behaviour killed his wife.<ref>{{cite web|last=Betz |first=Peter |url=http://epub.ub.uni-muenchen.de/7477/1/eisenmenger_wolfgang_7477.pdf |title=Homicide with  a Captive Bolt Pistol|publisher=Raven Press |date=1993 |accessdate=2012-10-27|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n* An English slaughterman killed a woman with two shots to the chest.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bolt-gun murder 'not predictable'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-suffolk-15636199|accessdate=2017-12-22|work=BBC News|date=8 November 2011}}</ref>\n* On 8 January, 2009, [[Sri Lanka]]n investigative journalist and founder Editor-in-Chief of ''[[The Sunday Leader]]'' [[Lasantha Wickrematunge]] was reportedly assassinated by Sri Lankan military operatives with the use of a captive bolt pistol. {{fact|date=July 2019}}\n\n===In fiction===\n* In the TV series ''[[Bones_(TV_series)|Bones]]'', the mother of protagonist [[Temperance \"Bones\" Brennan]] is discovered to have been murdered with a captive bolt pistol, which convicts a suspected hitman who evaded arrest for decades due to his favored murder weapon being unknown prior to this discovery.\n* In the novel ''[[No Country for Old Men]]'' and its [[No Country for Old Men (film)|film adaption]], [[Psychopathy|psychopathic]] [[hitman]] [[Anton Chigurh]] uses a captive bolt pistol as a murder weapon, as well as an impromptu breaking-and-entering device.\n* In Austrian director [[Michael Haneke]]'s 1992 film ''[[Benny's Video]]'', the murder of a young girl is perpetrated with a captive bolt pistol.\n* In the 2017 film ''[[It (2017 film)| It]]'', protagonist [[Bill Denbrough (character)|Bill Denbrough]] used the bolt pistol on [[It (character)| Pennywise]].\n* The song \"Captive Bolt Pistol\" by British [[death metal]] band [[Carcass (band)|Carcass]] describes the use of captive bolt pistols for slaughtering cattle and humans.\n* A veterinarian's \"horse gun\" is used as a murder weapon in the episode entitled \"Confection\" of the British TV series ''[[Endeavour (TV series)|Endeavour]]''.\n* In the 2020 film Bloodshot, Martin Axe uses a captive bolt gun to kill Ray\u2019s wife, Gina.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Captive bolt guns}}\n*[https://www.avma.org/KB/Policies/Documents/euthanasia.pdf AVMA Guidelines for the Euthanasia of Animals: 2013 Edition]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Captive Bolt Pistol}}\n[[Category:Firearms]]\n[[Category:Meat industry]]\n[[Category:Animal killing]]\n[[Category:Farming tools]]\n", "name_user": "Amybt79", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added description of Flesh House.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Captive_bolt_pistol"}
{"title_page": "Lovely (2012 film)", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Lovely\n| image = Lovely poster.jpg\n| alt =\n| caption = Film poster\n| director = [[B. Jaya]]\n| producer = {{plainlist|\n*[[R. R. Venkat]]\n*B.A. Raju\n}}\n| writer = B. Jaya\n| starring = {{plainlist|\n*[[Aadi (Telugu actor)|Aadi]]\n*[[Shanvi]]\n}}\n| music = [[Anoop Rubens]]\n| cinematography = S. Arun Kumar\n| editing = B. Jaya\n| studio = {{plainlist|\n*R. R. Movie Makers\n*RJ Cinemas\n}}\n| distributor = [[R. R. Movie Makers]]\n| released = {{Film date|df=yes|2012|3|30}}<ref name=\"ref1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.muvi.com/movies/lovely|title=Lovely Release Date|publisher=muvi.com|accessdate=24 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208162525/http://www.muvi.com/movies/lovely|archive-date=8 December 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| runtime =\n| country = India\n| language = Telugu\n| budget = {{INRConvert|10|c}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.muvi.com/movies/lovely|title=Lovely Budget|publisher=muvi.com|accessdate=24 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208162525/http://www.muvi.com/movies/lovely|archive-date=8 December 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| gross =\n}}\n\n'''''Lovely''''' is a 2012 [[Telugu-language]] [[romantic comedy]] film written and directed by [[B. Jaya]]. The film was produced by B. A. Raju and [[Anoop Rubens]] has composed the music for the film. The film stars [[Aadi (Telugu actor)|Aadi]] and [[Shanvi Srivastava]] in the lead roles. The film was a joint production between [[R. R. Movie Makers]] and RJ Cinemas. Alongside direction, both editing and screenplay were also handled by B. Jaya. The Movie was released on 30 March 2012<ref name=\"ref1\" /> and was a hit at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.manatelugu.in/2012/06/tollywood-hits-flops-in-first-half-2012.html|title=Tollywood Hits & Flops in First Half 2012|publisher=manatelugu.in|date=30 June 2012|accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref>\nIt was dubbed in to [[Hindi Language|Hindi]] as '''Vijay Meri Hai'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/lovely-hindi-version-sets-record-on-youtube-telugu-news-149936.html|title=\nWill Bolly director change Suriya's course? 'Lovely' Hindi version sets record on Youtube|publisher=indiaglitz.com|date=15 January 2016|accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref> The movie was remade in Odia in 2019 as ''Selfish Dil''.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Jk0yFECZ-NI</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nAkash ([[Aadi (Telugu actor)|Aadi]]) is a practical and easy going young guy and he does not have a very good opinion about women and love stories. His friend Kittu ([[Vennela Kishore]]) is in a Facebook relationship with a girl named Lalli (Chinmayee Ghatrazu). When the time comes to meet each other, Kittu develops cold feet and out of a fear of rejection, sends in Akash to meet Lalli. On the other side, Lalli decides to send her friend Lavanya ([[Shanvi]]) to the meeting. It is love at first sight for this \u2018new\u2019 couple and very soon, they develop a deep bond. Just when everything seems nice and rosy, Lavanya's father Mangalampalli Maharadhi ([[Gadde Rajendra Prasad|Rajendra Prasad]]) enters the scene and he is not impressed with Akash's behavior. It is now up to Akash to convince Maharadhi to change his mind.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Aadi (Telugu actor)|Aadi]] as Akash\n* [[Shanvi]] as Lavanya (Lovely)\n* [[Gadde Rajendra Prasad|Rajendra Prasad]] as Mangalampalli Maharadhi\n* [[Vennela Kishore]] as Kittu\n* Chinmayi as Lalli\n* [[Paruchuri Brothers|Parachuri Gopala Krishna]] as Lalli's father\n* [[Ahuti Prasad]] as Bunk Babu Rao\n* [[Harsha Vardhan]] as Akash's brother\n* [[Satya Krishnan]] as Akash's sister-in-law\n* Anchal as Anjali (Bunk Babu Rao's daughter)\n* [[Rahul Dev]] as David\n* [[Tanikella Bharani]] as School Principal\n* Kasi Vishwanath in a Special Appearance\n* Duvvasi Mohan as Lalli's Father's P.A.\n* [[Dhanraj (Telugu comedian)|Dhanraj]] in a Special Appearance\n\n== Production ==\nIt was announced that Aadi, Shanvi, Vennela kishore and other crew members will be in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chitramala.in/news/aadi-s-lovely-shooting-in-final-stage-127945.html|title=\nAadi\u2019s Lovely casting announced|publisher=chitramala.in|accessdate=23 December 2011 <!-- at 3:59 pm --> }}</ref> Dr. Rajendra Prasad played an important role in this film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chitramala.in/news/aadi-s-lovely-shooting-in-final-stage-127945.html|title=Aadi\u2019s Lovely shooting in production stage!|publisher=chitramala.in|accessdate=23 December 2011 <!-- at 3:59 pm --> }}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nThe film was released on 30 March 2012.<ref name=\"ref1\" />\n\n=== Critical reception ===\nThe \"entertainment.oneindia.in\" website has stated that \"Overall, the film is an okay film with some decent entertainment values\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/telugu/reviews/2012/lovely-movie-review-300312.html|title=Lovely \u2013 Movie Review|publisher=entertainment.oneindia.in|accessdate=30 March 2012<!--, 17:37 [IST]-->}}</ref>\n\n=== Box office ===\nThe film has completed 50 days on 18 May 2012 in 34 centres.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/lovely-completes-50-days-in-34-centres/259023-71-216.html|title='Lovely' completes 50 days in 34 centres|publisher=[[CNN-IBN]]|accessdate=18 May 2012 <!-- at 11:37am IST --> }}</ref> The film has completed 100 days run on 7 July 2012 in 12 centres.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/telugu/article/83572.html|title=Lovely completes 100 days in 12 centres|publisher=indiaglitz.com|accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Lovely\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Anup Rubens]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Album cover\n| released   = {{Start date|df=yes|2012|3|13}}\n| recorded   = 2012\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre 