{"title_page": "Edward Larocque Tinker", "text_new": "'''Edward Larocque Tinker''' ([[New York City]], September 12, 1881 \u2013 July 6, 1968 New York City){{citation needed|date=December 2018}} was an American writer and philanthropist who developed a deep interest in the culture of Latin America and spent much of his life exploring it. Tinker was the grandson of [[Joseph Larocque (attorney)|Joseph Larocque]]. He studied at Columbia University Law School. He achieved Ph.D.'s in literature from the [[University of Paris]] and the University of Madrid. He also wrote extensively on the culture and history of the city of [[New Orleans]].<ref>https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/edward-larocque-tinker/creole-city/</ref>\n\nHis mother Louise (Larocque) Tinker, his father was Henry Champlin Tinker, and he married Frances McKee on January 16, 1916.\n\nTinker created the Tinker Foundation in 1959 in memory of his second wife Frances McKee Tinker, his father Henry Champlin Tinker, and his grandfather Edward Greenfield Tinker.<ref>[http://www.tinker.org/content/history-foundation History of the Foundation.] The Tinker Foundation. Retrieved 2 September 2014.</ref>\n\nThe Edward Larocque Tinker Library is located at the [[Harry Ransom Center]], University of Texas at Austin.<ref>[http://www.hrc.utexas.edu/collections/books/holdings/tinker/ Edward Larocque Tinker Library.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127161330/http://www.hrc.utexas.edu/collections/books/holdings/tinker/ |date=2018-11-27 }} Harry Ransom Center, University of Texas at Austin. Retrieved 2 September 2014.</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*''Lafcadio Hearn's American Days'', 1924\n*''Closed Shutters: Old New Orleans - the Eighties'', 1931\n*''Les \u00e9crits de langue fran\u00e7aise en Louisiane au XIXe si\u00e8cle'', 1932\n*''The horsemen of the Americas and the literature they inspired'', 1953\n*''Gombo Comes to Philadelphia''1957\n*''Life and Literature of the Pampas'', 1961\n*''Centaurs of Many Lands'', 1964\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.tinker.org/  www.tinker.org]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tinker, Edward}}\n[[Category:1881 births]]\n[[Category:1968 deaths]]\n[[Category:American philanthropists]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century philanthropists]]\n\n\n{{US-activist-stub}}\n{{philanthropist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Edward Larocque Tinker''' ([[New York City]], September 12, 1881 \u2013 July 6, 1968 New York City){{citation needed|date=December 2018}} was an American writer and philanthropist who developed a deep interest in the culture of Latin America and spent much of his life exploring it. Tinker was the grandson of [[Joseph Larocque (attorney)|Joseph Larocque]]. He studied at Columbia University Law School. He achieved Ph.D.'s in literature from the [[University of Paris]] and the University of Madrid. He also wrote extensively on the culture and history of the city of [[New Orleans]].<ref>https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/edward-larocque-tinker/creole-city/</ref>\n\nHis mother Louise (Larocque) Tinker, his father was Henry Champlin Tinker, and he married Frances McKee on January 16, 1916.\n\nTinker created the Tinker Foundation in 1959 in memory of his second wife Frances McKee Tinker, his father Henry Champlin Tinker, and his grandfather Edward Greenfield Tinker.<ref>[http://www.tinker.org/content/history-foundation History of the Foundation.] The Tinker Foundation. Retrieved 2 September 2014.</ref>\n\nThe Edward Larocque Tinker Library is located at the [[Harry Ransom Center]], University of Texas at Austin.<ref>[http://www.hrc.utexas.edu/collections/books/holdings/tinker/ Edward Larocque Tinker Library.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127161330/http://www.hrc.utexas.edu/collections/books/holdings/tinker/ |date=2018-11-27 }} Harry Ransom Center, University of Texas at Austin. Retrieved 2 September 2014.</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*''Lafcadio Hearn's American Days'', 1924\n*''Closed Shutters: Old New Orleans - the Eighties'', 1931\n*''Les \u00e9crits de langue fran\u00e7aise en Louisiane au XIXe si\u00e8cle'', 1932\n*''The horsemen of the Americas and the literature they inspired'', 1953\n*''Gombo Comes to Philadelphia''1957\n*''Life and Literature of the Pampas'', 1961\n*''Centaurs of Many Lands'', 1964\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.tinker.org/  www.tinker.org]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tinker, Edward}}\n[[Category:1881 births]]\n[[Category:1968 deaths]]\n[[Category:American philanthropists]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century philanthropists]]\n\n\n{{US-activist-stub}}\n{{philanthropist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Larocque_Tinker"}
{"title_page": "Edward Lapworth", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n'''Edward Lapworth''' (1574\u20131636) was an English physician and Latin poet, and the first [[Sedleian]] reader at the University of Oxford.\n\n==Life==\nLapworth was a native of [[Warwickshire]]; his father was physician to [[Henry Berkeley, 7th Baron Berkeley|Henry Berkeley]]. He was admitted B.A. at [[St Alban Hall]], Oxford on 25 October 1592, and M.A. 30 June 1595. From 1598 to 1610 he was Master of [[Magdalen College School, Oxford|Magdalen College School]].<ref name=\"DNB\">{{cite DNB|wstitle=Lapworth, Edward|volume=32}}</ref>\n\nAs a member of [[Magdalen College, Oxford|Magdalen College]] Lapworth supplicated for the degree of M.B. and for licence to practise medicine 1 March 1602\u20133. He was licensed on 3 June 1605, and was admitted M.B. and M.D. on 20 June 1611.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\nLapworth was ''moderator in vesperiis'' in medicine in 1605 and 1611, and respondent in natural philosophy on [[James I]]'s visit to Oxford in 1605. In July 1611 he had permission to be absent from congregation in order that he might attend to his medical practice. In 1617 and 1619 he seems to have been in practice at [[Faversham]], Kent.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\nIn 1618 Lapworth was designated first Sedleian reader in natural philosophy under the will of the founder, [[William Sedley]], even though the bequest did not take effect till 1621; and on 9 August 1619 was appointed Linacre physic lecturer. From this time onwards he resided part of the year in Oxford. In the summer he practised usually at [[Bath, Somerset]]; and died there 23 May 1636, having resigned his Oxford lectureship the previous year. He was buried in [[Bath Abbey]].<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==Works==\nLapworth was a scholarly man who wrote [[occasional verse]], and was praised by [[John Davies of Hereford]].<ref name=\"DNB\"/><ref>{{cite book|author=Charles Henry Poole|title=Warwickshire poets|url=https://archive.org/details/warwickshirepoet00pool|year=1914|publisher=Ling|page=[https://archive.org/details/warwickshirepoet00pool/page/93 93]}}</ref> One known event with songs by him was the 1613 marriage of [[Robert Coke (MP for Coventry and Fowey)|Sir Robert Coke]] to Theophila Berkeley, daughter of [[Sir Thomas Berkeley]].<ref name=\"DNB\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1604-1629/member/coke-sir-robert-1587-1653|title=''Coke, Sir Robert (1587-1653),  of Caludon Castle, nr. Coventry, Warws. and Huntingfield, Suff.; later of Epsom, Surr.'', History of Parliament Online|accessdate=25 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nVerses by Lapworth occur in a number of books, and [[John Rouse Bloxam]] catalogued 13. Besides royal occasions, they commemorate  William, son of [[Arthur Grey, 14th Baron Grey de Wilton]]. He contributed to [[Joshua Sylvester]]'s ''Du Bartas, his Devine Weekes and Workes'', 1605, and the treatise of [[Edward Jorden]] on ''Naturall Bathes and Minerall Waters''.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==Family==\nLapworth married, first, Mary Coxhead, who was buried 2 January 1621; and, secondly, Margery, daughter of [[Sir George Snigg]] and widow of George Chaldecot of Quarlstone. He had a son, Michael, who matriculated at Magdalen College in 1621, aged 17; and a daughter, Anne, who was his heiress, and mother of [[William Joyner (playwright)|William Joyner]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n;Attribution\n\n{{DNB|wstitle=Lapworth, Edward|volume=32}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lapworth, Edward}}\n[[Category:1574 births]]\n[[Category:1636 deaths]]\n[[Category:17th-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:English male poets]]\n[[Category:17th-century male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n'''Edward Lapworth''' (1574\u20131636) was an English physician and Latin poet, and the first [[Sedleian]] reader at the University of Oxford.\n\n==Life==\nLapworth was a native of [[Warwickshire]]; his father was physician to [[Henry Berkeley, 7th Baron Berkeley|Henry Berkeley]]. He was admitted B.A. at [[St Alban Hall]], Oxford on 25 October 1592, and M.A. 30 June 1595. From 1598 to 1610 he was Master of [[Magdalen College School, Oxford|Magdalen College School]].<ref name=\"DNB\">{{cite DNB|wstitle=Lapworth, Edward|volume=32}}</ref>\n\nAs a member of [[Magdalen College, Oxford|Magdalen College]] Lapworth supplicated for the degree of M.B. and for licence to practise medicine 1 March 1602\u20133. He was licensed on 3 June 1605, and was admitted M.B. and M.D. on 20 June 1611.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\nLapworth was ''moderator in vesperiis'' in medicine in 1605 and 1611, and respondent in natural philosophy on [[James I]]'s visit to Oxford in 1605. In July 1611 he had permission to be absent from congregation in order that he might attend to his medical practice. In 1617 and 1619 he seems to have been in practice at [[Faversham]], Kent.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\nIn 1618 Lapworth was designated first Sedleian reader in natural philosophy under the will of the founder, [[William Sedley]], even though the bequest did not take effect till 1621; and on 9 August 1619 was appointed Linacre physic lecturer. From this time onwards he resided part of the year in Oxford. In the summer he practised usually at [[Bath, Somerset]]; and died there 23 May 1636, having resigned his Oxford lectureship the previous year. He was buried in [[Bath Abbey]].<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==Works==\nLapworth was a scholarly man who wrote [[occasional verse]], and was praised by [[John Davies of Hereford]].<ref name=\"DNB\"/><ref>{{cite book|author=Charles Henry Poole|title=Warwickshire poets|url=https://archive.org/details/warwickshirepoet00pool|year=1914|publisher=Ling|page=[https://archive.org/details/warwickshirepoet00pool/page/93 93]}}</ref> One known event with songs by him was the 1613 marriage of [[Robert Coke (MP for Coventry and Fowey)|Sir Robert Coke]] to Theophila Berkeley, daughter of [[Sir Thomas Berkeley]].<ref name=\"DNB\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1604-1629/member/coke-sir-robert-1587-1653|title=''Coke, Sir Robert (1587-1653),  of Caludon Castle, nr. Coventry, Warws. and Huntingfield, Suff.; later of Epsom, Surr.'', History of Parliament Online|accessdate=25 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nVerses by Lapworth occur in a number of books, and [[John Rouse Bloxam]] catalogued 13. Besides royal occasions, they commemorate  William, son of [[Arthur Grey, 14th Baron Grey de Wilton]]. He contributed to [[Joshua Sylvester]]'s ''Du Bartas, his Devine Weekes and Workes'', 1605, and the treatise of [[Edward Jorden]] on ''Naturall Bathes and Minerall Waters''.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==Family==\nLapworth married, first, Mary Coxhead, who was buried 2 January 1621; and, secondly, Margery, daughter of [[Sir George Snigg]] and widow of George Chaldecot of Quarlstone. He had a son, Michael, who matriculated at Magdalen College in 1621, aged 17; and a daughter, Anne, who was his heiress, and mother of [[William Joyner (playwright)|William Joyner]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n;Attribution\n\n{{DNB|wstitle=Lapworth, Edward|volume=32}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lapworth, Edward}}\n[[Category:1574 births]]\n[[Category:1636 deaths]]\n[[Category:17th-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:English male poets]]\n[[Category:17th-century male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotes:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Lapworth"}
